mediaObjects.heading: Why Go Prebuilt?
mediaObjects.copy: These gaming PCs aren't just built by experts, they're designed by them too! NZXT Prebuilt gaming PCs are made with budget and experience in mind.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Price
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy: Save on building fees and the cost of purchasing parts separately.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Quality
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy: Get the same high-quality components you would when purchasing a Custom PC.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Convenience
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy: Prebuilt Player PCs are assembled by experts, with a simple lineup of products to choose from.

mediaObjects.heading: Curated by us. Customized by you.
mediaObjects.copy: Make your Player PC your own with a selection of mighty upgrades. Power up and personalize—it's all in your hands now.

content.heading: Choosing the Right PC
content.subheading: Wondering how to choose a gaming PC? There are a few things to consider when buying a gaming PC.

cards.heading: Made For You
cards.subheading: Whether you're just getting started or in need of a powerhouse, each series is tailor-made for your goals.

cards.heading: Gaming
cards.subheading: Whether you want to play popular games, get eye-watering visuals, or hit peak FPS, our Prebuilts got you covered from mid-range to top-of-the-line GPUs and CPUs.

cards.heading: Streaming
cards.subheading: Ready to go live with your stream? We offer powerful CPUs, GPUs, and plenty capacity and performance so you can play and stream without taking a performance hit.

cards.heading: Creating
cards.subheading: Multitask like a pro with maxed out performance parts in our newest cases, allowing you to tackle more applications and increase your workflow. Our gaming PCs go beyond gaming.

cards.heading: Performance
cards.subheading: The Player PCs are a series of prebuilt gaming desktops with three models increasing in performance. The best way to figure out which PC suits your needs is to determine your performance and settings needs.

cards.heading: Latest Components
cards.subheading: Save time sourcing parts—we've done it for you. Player PCs have the best of previous and current gen chipsets and graphics cards.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Chipset
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy: Intel and AMD have similar performance and are both great options for a gaming PC. Some games benefit from having an Intel chipset or an AMD chipset. We'll help you build both, and we pick motherboards and coolers that work well together so you don't have to research. The chipset will impact some of the other components in your case, such as your motherboard.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Cases
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
The H Series is our signature line of all-steel cases featuring a tempered glass side panel. The H Series ranges in size from mini-ITX to mid-tower. Mid-tower (H710) and compact mid-tower (H510) are the most common form factors and have plenty of space for most builds. Wondering which case is right for you? The first step is determine your desired footprint--how much space do you want your PC to take up? Whether you're in a dorm room or a generously-sized office, the H Series has a range of sizes ready to house your dream build.
 
 Smaller cases (H210, H1) require smaller motherboards and will limit the type and amount of components that can fit inside the case. Once you determine which form factor you prefer, the configurator will narrow down the components you can select.
 
** Pro tip!** If you find that your preferred GPU (or any component) is in-stock but unavailable, you may want to revisit your case selection.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Services
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy: This section is for the service we provide for your gaming PC! Our standard service includes assembly of your PC, operating system setup, and a two year warranty with access to our live support team on chat, email, and phones! Expedited shipping and building options are available when possible.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Software
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
Microsoft offers two editions of their operating system: Windows 11 Home and Pro editions.
 
For most customers, we recommend Windows 11 Home. This edition provides all the key features your PC would need to work properly for daily use. For customers who may work in an industry that relies on protecting critical information or for customers who need enterprise productivity and management features, we recommend Windows 11 Pro.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Extras
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy: This section provides options for additional accessories to help you stay organized, enhance your connectability, or add functionality to your build.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Peripherals
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy: Peripherals help you get more out of your build. Some peripherals are a must, like keyboard and monitor. Some, however, are simply a great way to personalize your game space or provide added functionality.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Monitors
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
Monitors (sometimes referred to as displays) can have a massive impact on your gaming experience. We currently offer two types of monitors, VA and IPS monitors. What's the difference?
 
* VA panels provide great color contrast and display black colors accurately, and are a great option for an affordable gaming display. 
 
* IPS panels are known for having more accurate colors to help produce a higher quality image on your monitor. IPS panels also have better viewing angles and are able to maintain fast-moving images without producing afterimages (ghosting). 
 
 Monitors come in different resolutions. Some common resolutions are 1080p, 1440p, and 4K. The resolution determines the number of pixels in your monitor; the higher the resolution, the higher quality image that is produced. 
 
 A monitor's speed is also important to your gaming experience. This is quantified in two numbers: the "Response Rate" and "Hz." Response rate is how quickly your display is able to change its pixels, the lower the number the better. The Hz (Hertz) is the number of cycles per second it is able to physically display, and this number is directly linked to the FPS you will be able to see. If a monitor is 144hz, this would mean that 144 FPS can be seen on the monitor.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Lighting
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy: RGB products are a great way to personalize your build. You can mix and match any NZXT RGB accessories to add vibrant accents almost anywhere on your PC. The H510 Elite and i version cases include an RGB and Fan Controller. Adding a controller along with additional RGB products allows for adjustment of the color and effects of your lighting accessories, as well as adjust fan curves and speeds through NZXT CAM.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Storage
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
Your storage device is where your operating system, applications, and files will be saved to. We offer several different kinds of storage options and their speeds for these devices are measured in MB/s (Megabytes per Second). The speed of your storage device dictates how fast your computer can retrieve information from storage.
 
Typically, the faster your storage device, the better. However, extremely high-speed storage will ultimately have no impact on visible performance. Speeds of 3000 MB/s or above will mostly benefit content creators, as this can reduce load times and improve performance for high-resolution video editing. When selecting storage, keep in mind we will always install your operating system to the fastest storage device in your build to make sure you have the best experience with your PC. 
 
**Pro tip!** Most games these days can be fairly large, so we recommend a minimum of 1TB of storage. This will prevent you from filling up your storage too quickly.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: RAM
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
RAM is a special type of memory specifically designed to temporarily hold information on applications and games your PC may be running. 
 
 Think of your storage like a kitchen. Your hard drive is all the space you have to store things in the cabinets and your refrigerator. Your RAM is your countertop--it houses all of the things you're working on right now. The more counter space you have, the more ingredients you can take out at once. Likewise, the more RAM you have, the more processes your PC can handle simultaneously.
 
 The size and speed of your RAM are important for the performance of your PC. Size is measured in GB (Gigabytes) and speed is measured in MHz. We recommend a minimum of 16GBs of RAM for general multitasking and gaming. How fast your RAM is will determine how responsive your PC will be to performing tasks on your system. RAM has little affect on framerate but will provide a meaningful impact on the usability of your PC.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Power Supplies
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
The PSU is what sends power to all of your components within your PC. A power supply is designed to pull in power from the wall and output a certain amount of wattage safely and consistently to your PC. 
 
 When selecting a PSU, keep in mind that the configurator automatically selects the best power supply that would support your PC, wattage-wise. You may notice the terms Bronze/Gold being used when referring to the PSU. This is the efficiency of your PSU and this certification comes in the following levels: Bronze, Silver, Gold, Platinum, and Titanium. 
 
 The higher the certification, the more efficient your PSU is. More efficient PSUs result in a lower power bill in the long run, and less excess heat for your components!
 
**Pro tip!** Many gaming setups work perfectly fine with a Bronze PSU. Upgrade to Gold if it is recommended by the Configurator or if you plan on upgrading your GPU in the future.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: CPU
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
The CPU is kind of like the brain of your build. It's responsible for coordinating all of the components connected to your PC in order for the system to run and therefore will have an impact on your in-game FPS.

Pro tip! Key features to look for in a processor:

*  Number of Cores
*  GHz Clock Speed

A core is a logical processor that does all the heavy lifting, so the more cores you have, the more simultaneous processing can occur. For gaming, a quad or six-core processor is needed for good performance. 8-10 core processors are better for streaming/content creation but aren't necessary for gaming only. 
 GHz (Gigahertz) clock speed determines how fast your CPU can process a task.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Motherboard
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
The motherboard is the central hub of your PC that allows each of your components to communicate with one another. We typically recommend that you select a motherboard that has the relative value of your CPU. If the cost/value of your motherboard is well below the cost/value of your CPU, you may miss out on some features and functionality. 
 
**Pro tip!** Here are some features to look for when purchasing a motherboard: 
* Built-in WiFi
* Max Supported RAM MHz
* Gigabit Ethernet 
* Optical Audio
* USB Type-C Support
 
Motherboards don't affect your game performance, so it's best to pick a motherboard that meets your needs and budget and corresponds to the value of your desired CPU.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: Cooling
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
NZXT offers two types of cooling solutions, All-in-one liquid coolers and air coolers. What's the difference?
 
* All-in-one liquid (AIO) coolers keep the processor cool by circulating a liquid solution through an integrated radiator and pump. This liquid is cooled by airflow passing through the radiator of the cooling system with the included fan(s). AIOs accomplish both form and function due to their sleek design and are a favorite among those who prioritize the aesthetic quality of their build.
 
* Air coolers reduce the temperature of a processor through a set of heat pipes that will conduct heat to a set of air fins. These fins are then cooled by a fan pushing air through the cooler.
 
** Pro tip!** For high-performance processors, such as Intel i7/AMD Ryzen 7 or higher, we recommend a liquid cooler. However, an air cooler is still a great choice for many builds and can provide sufficient and cost-effective cooling.
 
 This section also includes additional fan options. Our cases and coolers include required fans. These options allow you to customize or improve aesthetics and airflow, with professional cable management.

markdownIconBlocks.heading: GPU
markdownIconBlocks.markdownCopy:
The GPU is considered by many to be one of the most important components in your build. That's because it has one of the most important jobs: rendering what you do on your PC to your display!
 
 GPUs have the largest impact on gaming FPS, and you can see this in real-time when cycling through the numerous GPU options in the configurator. When picking a GPU, it is recommended to get the best card in your budget without downgrading other components.
 
 Pro tip! Here are a couple features you should be keeping an eye out for when considering GPUs:
 • GPU VRAM 
 • Core Clock Speed
 • Boost Clock speed
 
 We recommend a minimum of 6GB of VRAM. Anything higher than 6 is great to have and directly impacts the quality of many of your favorite games. A higher Core/Boost Clock speed will also help improve your FPS.
